            <h2 style="color: #2e7d32; margin-bottom: 10px;">Axaftina Rasterast/Nerasterast</h2>
            <h3 style="color: #666; margin-bottom: 30px; font-weight: normal;">Direct & Indirect Speech</h3>

            <!-- INTRODUCTION -->
            <div style="background: #e3f2fd; padding: 25px; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 30px; border-left: 5px solid #2196f3;">
                <h3 style="color: #1976d2; margin-bottom: 15px;">üìå What is Direct and Indirect Speech?</h3>
                <p style="line-height: 1.8; font-size: 1.05rem;">
                    <strong>Direct speech</strong> (Axaftina Rasterast) reports the exact words someone said, using quotation marks.
                </p>
                <p style="line-height: 1.8; font-size: 1.05rem; margin-top: 10px;">
                    <strong>Indirect speech</strong> (Axaftina Nerasterast) reports what someone said without using their exact words.
                </p>
                <div class="quote-box" style="margin-top: 20px;">
                    <strong>Direct:</strong> Ew got: "Ez dixwazim herim."<br>
                    (He said: "I want to go.")<br><br>
                    <strong>Indirect:</strong> Ew got ku ew dixwaze here.<br>
                    (He said that he wanted to go.)
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- SECTION 1: DIRECT SPEECH -->
            <div class="speech-section">
                <div class="speech-title">1. Direct Speech (Axaftina Rasterast)</div>
                <div class="speech-subtitle">Quoting exact words</div>

                <div class="explanation">
                    <p>
                        In <strong>direct speech</strong>, we report the exact words someone said. In Kurdish, quotation marks 
                        are used, and the reporting verb is typically <strong>gotin</strong> (to say).
                    </p>
                </div>

                <div class="formula-box">
                    <strong>Direct Speech Structure:</strong><br>
                    Subject + gotin: "Quoted sentence"<br><br>
                    Examples:<br>
                    ‚Ä¢ Ew got: "<strong>Ez dixwazim herim.</strong>"<br>
                    ‚Ä¢ Min got: "<strong>Tu li ku y√Æ?</strong>"<br>
                    ‚Ä¢ Em gotin: "<strong>Em k√™fxwe≈ü in.</strong>"
                </div>

                <h4 style="color: #2e7d32; margin-top: 30px; margin-bottom: 15px;">Common Reporting Verbs:</h4>

                <table class="comparison-table">
                    <thead>
                        <tr>
                            <th>Kurdish Verb</th>
                            <th>English</th>
                            <th>Example (Kurdish)</th>
                            <th>Example (English)</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr>
                            <td><span class="direct-badge">gotin</span></td>
                            <td>to say</td>
                            <td>Ew got: "Ez ba≈ü im."</td>
                            <td>He said: "I am well."</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><span class="direct-badge">pirs√Æn</span></td>
                            <td>to ask</td>
                            <td>Ew pirs√Æ: "Tu √ßawa y√Æ?"</td>
                            <td>He asked: "How are you?"</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><span class="direct-badge">bersivdan</span></td>
                            <td>to answer</td>
                            <td>Ez bersiv dam: "Ez ba≈ü im."</td>
                            <td>I answered: "I am well."</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><span class="direct-badge">q√Ær√Æn</span></td>
                            <td>to shout</td>
                            <td>Ew q√Ær√Æya: "B√™ne vir!"</td>
                            <td>He shouted: "Come here!"</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><span class="direct-badge">axaftin</span></td>
                            <td>to speak</td>
                            <td>Ew axiv√Æ: "Ez dixwazim herim."</td>
                            <td>He spoke: "I want to go."</td>
                        </tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>

                <div class="example-box">
                    <div class="example-title">üìå Direct Speech Examples:</div>
                    
                    <div class="example-item">
                        <div class="kurdish-text">Min got: "Ez dixwazim pirt√ªkek bixw√Ænim."</div>
                        <div class="english-text">I said: "I want to read a book."</div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="example-item">
                        <div class="kurdish-text">Ew pirs√Æ: "Tu li ku y√Æ?"</div>
                        <div class="english-text">He asked: "Where are you?"</div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="example-item">
                        <div class="kurdish-text">Em gotin: "Em √™ sibe herin bajar√™."</div>
                        <div class="english-text">We said: "We will go to the city tomorrow."</div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="example-item">
                        <div class="kurdish-text">Tu got√Æ: "Ez nikarim b√™m."</div>
                        <div class="english-text">You said: "I cannot come."</div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="note-box">
                    <div class="note-title">üí° Punctuation Note!</div>
                    <p style="line-height: 1.8;">
                        In Kurdish direct speech:<br>
                        ‚Ä¢ Use quotation marks: <strong>"..."</strong><br>
                        ‚Ä¢ Place a colon <strong>:</strong> before the quote<br>
                        ‚Ä¢ Keep the original tense and pronouns<br>
                        ‚Ä¢ Capitalize the first word inside quotes
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- SECTION 2: INDIRECT SPEECH -->
            <div class="speech-section">
                <div class="speech-title">2. Indirect Speech (Axaftina Nerasterast)</div>
                <div class="speech-subtitle">Reporting what was said</div>

                <div class="explanation">
                    <p>
                        In <strong>indirect speech</strong>, we report what someone said without using their exact words. 
                        The conjunction <strong>ku</strong> (that) is used to introduce the reported clause.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <div class="formula-box">
                    <strong>Indirect Speech Structure:</strong><br>
                    Subject + gotin + ku + Reported clause<br><br>
                    Examples:<br>
                    ‚Ä¢ Ew got <strong>ku</strong> ew dixwaze here.<br>
                    ‚Ä¢ Min got <strong>ku</strong> ez ba≈ü im.<br>
                    ‚Ä¢ Em gotin <strong>ku</strong> em √™ herin.
                </div>

                <h4 style="color: #2e7d32; margin-top: 30px; margin-bottom: 15px;">Direct to Indirect Transformation:</h4>

                <table class="comparison-table">
                    <thead>
                        <tr>
                            <th>Direct Speech</th>
                            <th>Indirect Speech</th>
                            <th>English (Direct)</th>
                            <th>English (Indirect)</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr>
                            <td><span class="direct-badge">Ew got: "Ez ba≈ü im."</span></td>
                            <td><span class="indirect-badge">Ew got ku ew ba≈ü e.</span></td>
                            <td>He said: "I am well."</td>
                            <td>He said that he was well.</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><span class="direct-badge">Min got: "Ez dixwazim herim."</span></td>
                            <td><span class="indirect-badge">Min got ku ez dixwazim herim.</span></td>
                            <td>I said: "I want to go."</td>
                            <td>I said that I wanted to go.</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><span class="direct-badge">Tu got√Æ: "Ez li mal√™ me."</span></td>
                            <td><span class="indirect-badge">Tu got√Æ ku tu li mal√™ y√Æ.</span></td>
                            <td>You said: "I am at home."</td>
                            <td>You said that you were at home.</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><span class="direct-badge">Ew got: "Ez √™ b√™m."</span></td>
                            <td><span class="indirect-badge">Ew got ku ew √™ were.</span></td>
                            <td>He said: "I will come."</td>
                            <td>He said that he would come.</td>
                        </tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>

                <div class="note-box">
                    <div class="note-title">üí° Key Changes!</div>
                    <p style="line-height: 1.8;">
                        When converting to indirect speech:<br>
                        ‚Ä¢ Remove quotation marks<br>
                        ‚Ä¢ Add <strong>ku</strong> (that) after the reporting verb<br>
                        ‚Ä¢ Change pronouns (ez ‚Üí ew, min ‚Üí w√Æ/w√™)<br>
                        ‚Ä¢ Adjust verb forms if necessary<br>
                        ‚Ä¢ Change time/place references (√Æro ‚Üí w√™ roj√™, vir ‚Üí wir)
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- SECTION 3: PRONOUN CHANGES -->
            <div class="speech-section">
                <div class="speech-title">3. Pronoun Changes in Indirect Speech</div>
                <div class="speech-subtitle">Adjusting personal pronouns</div>

                <div class="explanation">
                    <p>
                        When converting from direct to indirect speech, pronouns must be changed to reflect 
                        the perspective of the reporter.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <h4 style="color: #2e7d32; margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 15px;">Pronoun Transformations:</h4>

                <table class="comparison-table">
                    <thead>
                        <tr>
                            <th>Direct Speech Pronoun</th>
                            <th>Indirect Speech Pronoun</th>
                            <th>Example (Direct)</th>
                            <th>Example (Indirect)</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr>
                            <td>ez (I)</td>
                            <td>ew (he/she)</td>
                            <td>Ew got: "Ez ba≈ü im."</td>
                            <td>Ew got ku ew ba≈ü e.</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>min (I - oblique)</td>
                            <td>w√Æ/w√™ (him/her)</td>
                            <td>Ew got: "Min d√Æt."</td>
                            <td>Ew got ku w√Æ d√Ætiye.</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>tu (you)</td>
                            <td>ew (he/she)</td>
                            <td>Min got: "Tu ba≈ü √Æ."</td>
                            <td>Min got ku ew ba≈ü e.</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>em (we)</td>
                            <td>ew (they)</td>
                            <td>Em gotin: "Em herin."</td>
                            <td>Em gotin ku em herin.</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>h√ªn (you pl.)</td>
                            <td>ew (they)</td>
                            <td>Ew got: "H√ªn ba≈ü in."</td>
                            <td>Ew got ku ew ba≈ü in.</td>
                        </tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>

                <div class="example-box">
                    <div class="example-title">üìå Pronoun Change Examples:</div>
                    
                    <div class="example-item">
                        <div class="kurdish-text"><strong>Direct:</strong> Ew got: "Ez dixwazim pirt√ªkek bixw√Ænim."</div>
                        <div class="english-text">He said: "I want to read a book."</div>
                        <div class="kurdish-text" style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Indirect:</strong> Ew got ku ew dixwaze pirt√ªkek bixw√Æne.</div>
                        <div class="english-text">He said that he wanted to read a book.</div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="example-item">
                        <div class="kurdish-text"><strong>Direct:</strong> Min got: "Tu pir ba≈ü √Æ."</div>
                        <div class="english-text">I said: "You are very good."</div>
                        <div class="kurdish-text" style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Indirect:</strong> Min got ku ew pir ba≈ü e.</div>
                        <div class="english-text">I said that he/she was very good.</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- SECTION 4: TENSE CHANGES -->
            <div class="speech-section">
                <div class="speech-title">4. Tense Changes in Indirect Speech</div>
                <div class="speech-subtitle">Sequence of tenses</div>

                <div class="explanation">
                    <p>
                        In Kurdish, tense changes in indirect speech are <strong>less strict</strong> than in English. 
                        Often, the original tense is maintained, especially when the statement is still true.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <h4 style="color: #2e7d32; margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 15px;">Tense Transformations:</h4>

                <table class="comparison-table">
                    <thead>
                        <tr>
                            <th>Direct Speech Tense</th>
                            <th>Indirect Speech Tense</th>
                            <th>Example (Direct)</th>
                            <th>Example (Indirect)</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Present</td>
                            <td>Present (often unchanged)</td>
                            <td>Ew got: "Ez dixw√Ænim."</td>
                            <td>Ew got ku ew dixw√Æne.</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Past</td>
                            <td>Past (unchanged)</td>
                            <td>Ew got: "Min xwend."</td>
                            <td>Ew got ku w√Æ xwendiye.</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Future (√™)</td>
                            <td>Future (often unchanged)</td>
                            <td>Ew got: "Ez √™ herim."</td>
                            <td>Ew got ku ew √™ here.</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Present Perfect</td>
                            <td>Present Perfect</td>
